Organizing data

  • Can we always plot the data without reorganizing it?

  • There are two types of reorganizations
    • reshape the data
    • transform the data

  • Reshaping the data is needed when we want to map the variable to an aesthetic but variable is not explicitly available

  • Transforming is needed when some theoretical/ mathematical model is fitted or associated with the data

Data in wide form

  • What are the variables in the table shown below?
year online-sale store-sale
2010 20 25
2011 24 31
2012 35 40
  • This is a wide form table
  • Are the variables in the table same as the variables in the plot?
ggplot(dat, aes(year, sales, color=type)) + 
  geom_line()
  • What are the variables in the data that produces the plot below?

  • What are the variables in the table shown below?
year sales type

  • This is a long form table
  • Are the variables in the table same as the variables in the plot?

Long vs wide form data

  • How can we switch between long form and wide form of data
    • install.packages(rehsape2)
    • there are two functions
      • melt() melts data to long form
      • dcast() shapes molten data to wide form
  • cast() function has some other variations
    • acast() is for array type data
    • dcast() is for data frame

French fries data

  • Some data from R data frame french_fries
##  time treatment subject rep potato buttery grassy rancid painty
##     1         1       3   1    2.9     0.0    0.0    0.0    5.5
##     1         1       3   2   14.0     0.0    0.0    1.1    0.0
##     1         1      10   1   11.0     6.4    0.0    0.0    0.0
##     1         1      10   2    9.9     5.9    2.9    2.2    0.0

##     1         1      15   2    8.8     3.0    3.6    1.5    2.3
  • How can we visualize the relationships between replication 1 and 2 for each of the sensory attributes?
  • Discuss with your neighbor and prepare a plan.
  • Solution: generate scatterplot of rep1 vs rep2
    • we need to melt the data, except time, treatment, subject and rep
    • finally cast the data as the form we want to create scatterplot

Molten French fries data

  • first we melt the french_fries data
molten_fries <- melt(french_fries, id=1:4)
print(head(molten_fries), row.names=FALSE)
##  time treatment subject rep variable value
##     1         1       3   1   potato   2.9
##     1         1       3   2   potato  14.0
##     1         1      10   1   potato  11.0
##     1         1      10   2   potato   9.9
##     1         1      15   1   potato   1.2
##     1         1      15   2   potato   8.8
  • now we need two variables rep1 and rep2 for the scatterplot
  • we can do this by casting this molten data
  • while casting we need to keep variables time treatment subject intact

Casting French fries data

  • we used formula time + treatment + subject + variable ~ rep
  • it allows us to fix variables time, treatment, subject and variable
  • it creates two new columns 1 and 2
cast_fries <- dcast(molten_fries, time + treatment + subject + variable~rep, 
                    mean, value.var="value", na.rm=TRUE)
head(cast_fries)
##   time treatment subject variable    1    2
## 1    1         1       3   potato  2.9 14.0
## 2    1         1       3  buttery  0.0  0.0
## 3    1         1       3   grassy  0.0  0.0
## 4    1         1       3   rancid  0.0  1.1
## 5    1         1       3   painty  5.5  0.0
## 6    1         1      10   potato 11.0  9.9

Casting French fries data

  • we rename those new columns to be rep1 and rep2
colnames(cast_fries) <- c("time", "treatment", "subject" , "variable", "rep1","rep2")
head(cast_fries)
##   time treatment subject variable rep1 rep2
## 1    1         1       3   potato  2.9 14.0
## 2    1         1       3  buttery  0.0  0.0
## 3    1         1       3   grassy  0.0  0.0
## 4    1         1       3   rancid  0.0  1.1
## 5    1         1       3   painty  5.5  0.0
## 6    1         1      10   potato 11.0  9.9
  • now the data is ready to be plotted

Plotting French fries data

ggplot(cast_fries, aes(rep1, rep2)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~variable, nrow=1)

  • The correlation looks strong for potatoey and buttery, and poor for rancid and painty

Plotting French fries data

ggplot(cast_fries, aes(rep1, rep2, color=treatment)) + 
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~variable, nrow=1)

  • Similar behavior is observed for each treatment

Transforming data

ggplot(sdat, aes(x)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..))+
  geom_density(color='hotpink', size=1.1)

ggplot(sdat, aes(log(x+0.5))) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..))+
  geom_density(color='hotpink', size=1.1)

Transforming data

ggplot(sdat, aes(x,y)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth(method="lm")

ggplot(sdat, aes(log(x),log(y))) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method="lm")

Standardization of data

  • To compare the similarity of distributions of data in different scales
  • Types
    • Scale standardization (eg. percentage)
    • Location standardization
    • Scale and location \[y = \frac{x- \mu}{\sigma}\]
    • Compare quantiles (QQ-plot)
  • The goal is to compare shapes of the distribution not actual distribution

Aggregating data

Package dplyr

  • Fast aggregation of large data (e.g. 100GB in RAM)
## install.packages("dplyr")
library(dplyr)
  • Provides functions of these verbs
  • filter()
  • select()
  • arrange()
  • mutate()
  • summarize()
  • Other important functions
  • group_by()
  • summarise_each()

Piping or chain operation

  • Filter then select then arrange then mutate
    • We can do all these steps on the fly
    • Piping %>% like UNIX pipe |
tips %>% 
  filter(size > 5) %>% 
  select(total_bill, tip, sex, day, size) %>% 
  arrange(tip) %>% 
  mutate(tiprate = tip/total_bill)
##   total_bill tip    sex  day size   tiprate
## 1      29.80 4.2 Female Thur    6 0.1409396
## 2      27.05 5.0 Female Thur    6 0.1848429
## 3      48.17 5.0   Male  Sun    6 0.1037990
## 4      34.30 6.7   Male Thur    6 0.1953353

Complex chain operation

tips %>% 
  filter(size > 3) %>% 
  select(total_bill, tip, sex, day, size) %>% 
  arrange(tip) %>% 
  mutate(tiprate=tip/total_bill) %>%
    select(total_bill, tip, sex, day, tiprate) %>% 
    group_by(sex, day) %>%
    summarise_each(funs(mean)) %>%
    filter(tiprate > 0.12)
## # A tibble: 5 x 5
## # Groups:   sex [2]
##   sex    day   total_bill   tip tiprate
##   <fct>  <fct>      <dbl> <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1 Female Sun         29.9  4.54   0.152
## 2 Female Thur        31.8  4.46   0.142
## 3 Male   Sat         30.5  4.26   0.140
## 4 Male   Sun         27.1  4.00   0.152
## 5 Male   Thur        30.8  4.92   0.165

Joining or merging data

  • Package dplyr joining functions
    • inner_join
    • left_join
    • semi_join
    • anti_join
  • Generate two dataframes DT and W
    • Join DT and W only with matching column x.
DT <- data.frame(x = rep( 
  c("a","b","c"), times=c(3,2,2)), 
  y = 10:16, v = 1:7)
W <- data.frame(x=c("b","c","d"), 
                foo=c(4,2,9))
DT
##   x  y v
## 1 a 10 1
## 2 a 11 2
## 3 a 12 3
## 4 b 13 4
## 5 b 14 5
## 6 c 15 6
## 7 c 16 7
W
##   x foo
## 1 b   4
## 2 c   2
## 3 d   9

Joining or merging data

inner_join(DT,W)
##   x  y v foo
## 1 b 13 4   4
## 2 b 14 5   4
## 3 c 15 6   2
## 4 c 16 7   2
  • Some rows of DT and W are not returned.
left_join(DT,W)
##   x  y v foo
## 1 a 10 1  NA
## 2 a 11 2  NA
## 3 a 12 3  NA
## 4 b 13 4   4
## 5 b 14 5   4
## 6 c 15 6   2
## 7 c 16 7   2

Joining or merging data

anti_join(DT,W)
##   x  y v
## 1 a 10 1
## 2 a 11 2
## 3 a 12 3
  • anti_join() joins and subsets the data on the left dataframe
    • such that it does not exist in the other dataframe
semi_join(DT,W)
##   x  y v
## 1 b 13 4
## 2 b 14 5
## 3 c 15 6
## 4 c 16 7
  • semi_join() subsets the data on the right dataframe that does not belong to left dataframe

Complete cases and duplication

df <- data.frame(
    x = c(1:3,2,4),
    y=c("A","B",NA,"B","D"))
df
##   x    y
## 1 1    A
## 2 2    B
## 3 3 <NA>
## 4 2    B
## 5 4    D
df %>% filter(
  complete.cases(df))
##   x y
## 1 1 A
## 2 2 B
## 3 2 B
## 4 4 D
df %>% filter(
  complete.cases(df)) %>%
  filter(!duplicated(cbind(x,y)))
##   x y
## 1 1 A
## 2 2 B
## 3 4 D

Example codes (US crime map)

library(maps)
library(reshape2)
library(dplyr)
mdat <- map_data("state")
state <- tolower(row.names(USArrests))
arrest <- data.frame(state, USArrests, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
odat <- left_join(mdat, arrest, by = c('region' = 'state')) %>%
  arrange(order)
sdat <- subset(odat, select=c("long", "lat", "group", "region", "Murder",
                               "Assault", "UrbanPop",  "Rape" ))
 
msdat <- melt(sdat, id=c("long", "lat", "group", "region"))

ggplot(msdat, aes(x=long, y=lat,group=group)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(fill=value), colour = alpha("white", 1/2), size = 0.2) +
  theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = "none") + facet_wrap(~variable) +
  scale_fill_continuous(low="blue", high="hotpink")

Example codes (Crime with standardisation of data)

library(scales)
std_crime <- scale(USArrests)
arrest <- data.frame(state, std_crime, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
odat <- left_join(mdat, arrest, by = c('region' = 'state')) %>%
  arrange(order)
sdat <- subset(odat, select=c("long", "lat", "group", "region", "Murder",
                               "Assault", "UrbanPop",  "Rape" ))
 
msdat <- melt(sdat, id=c("long", "lat", "group", "region"))

ggplot(msdat, aes(x=long, y=lat,group=group)) +
  geom_polygon(aes(fill=value), colour = alpha("white", 1/2), size = 0.2) +
  theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = "none") + facet_wrap(~variable) +
  scale_fill_continuous(low="blue", high="hotpink")
